    "result": {"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p><em>In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will continue to talk about the fundamental of modeling in Blender.</em></p>\n<hr>\n<p>In the <a href=\"/2018/04/03/blender-tutorial-3-modeling-basics-part-1/\">previous post of the series \"Blender tutorial\"</a> we\nintroduced the first part of basics of modeling. Let's continue our exploration with other useful tool we can use for\nmodeling.<br>\nLet's start with <strong>Sculpt mode</strong>. We can enable it in the <em>editing/interaction mode selector</em> in the bottom bar of the\n3D window. In this mode you can literally sculpt you mesh. It possible to customize the sculpt mode by setting some of\nits properties:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>radius of the sculpt</em></li>\n<li><em>feather of the sculpt, that changes how the sculpt fall-off</em></li>\n<li><em>auto smooth</em></li>\n<li><em>add/subtract to pull in/out vertices while sculpting</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/83f39c3a53ef521f4677b0c0e6127ae8/c58a3/blender-sculpting.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.859649122807014%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Sculpting mode\"\n        title=\"Sculpting mode\"\n        src=\"/static/83f39c3a53ef521f4677b0c0e6127ae8/0470c/blender-sculpting.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/83f39c3a53ef521f4677b0c0e6127ae8/6c669/blender-sculpting.jpg 285w,\n/static/83f39c3a53ef521f4677b0c0e6127ae8/882a4/blender-sculpting.jpg 570w,\n/static/83f39c3a53ef521f4677b0c0e6127ae8/0470c/blender-sculpting.jpg 1140w,\n/static/83f39c3a53ef521f4677b0c0e6127ae8/c58a3/blender-sculpting.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Sculpting mode</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Sculpt mode supports also paint textures and strokes. But more important it supports symmetry: by selecting and axis any\nchange on one side will be mirrored on the other one.<br>\nAnother interesting option is the <strong>edge loop modeling</strong>. Basically this means that if we select a edge loop with <em>alt +\nright click</em> in edit mode/edge select mode, we can modify the edge loop by using the 3D axis that are shown after the\nselection. The next tool available for modeling is the <strong>extrude tool</strong>. With this tool we can modify our geometry and\nmore details. In particular, we can use it to create branches, legs and other parts that are out of the main body of the\nmesh. We can activate the extrude under <em>Mesh tools -> Extrude Region/Individual</em>. The extrude region will push out the\nelements selected as a single block. The extrude individual will extrude the elements selected individually.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/169f6364e62a5e21ab737cac26b69192/c58a3/blender-extrude.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.859649122807014%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The extrude tool\"\n        title=\"The extrude tool\"\n        src=\"/static/169f6364e62a5e21ab737cac26b69192/0470c/blender-extrude.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/169f6364e62a5e21ab737cac26b69192/6c669/blender-extrude.jpg 285w,\n/static/169f6364e62a5e21ab737cac26b69192/882a4/blender-extrude.jpg 570w,\n/static/169f6364e62a5e21ab737cac26b69192/0470c/blender-extrude.jpg 1140w,\n/static/169f6364e62a5e21ab737cac26b69192/c58a3/blender-extrude.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The extrude tool</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Another useful tool that we can use for modeling is <strong>smooth shading</strong>. We can use these to smooth the surface of\nobjects where the polygons of the mesh have too much hard edges. We can find the it under <em>Tools -> Shading</em> while an\nobject is selected in Object mode or under <em>Shading -> Faces/Edges/Vertices</em> while an object is in Edit mode.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/5ab9b62e6d1928f447e1f10ce72c9165/c58a3/blender-smooth-shading.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.859649122807014%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Smooth shading\"\n        title=\"Smooth shading\"\n        src=\"/static/5ab9b62e6d1928f447e1f10ce72c9165/0470c/blender-smooth-shading.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/5ab9b62e6d1928f447e1f10ce72c9165/6c669/blender-smooth-shading.jpg 285w,\n/static/5ab9b62e6d1928f447e1f10ce72c9165/882a4/blender-smooth-shading.jpg 570w,\n/static/5ab9b62e6d1928f447e1f10ce72c9165/0470c/blender-smooth-shading.jpg 1140w,\n/static/5ab9b62e6d1928f447e1f10ce72c9165/c58a3/blender-smooth-shading.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Smooth shading</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>The last tool we can use for some simple modeling is the <strong>subdividing mesh tool</strong>. There are two ways to do\nsubdivision:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>subdivision of the mesh itself</em></li>\n<li><em>subdivision surface</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now we will look at subdivision of the mesh itself. To do it we need to be in edit mode on the object and select all\nwith the <em>a key</em>. We can find the subdivision option under <em>Tools -> Subdivide</em>. If we click on that a series of\nsubdivision properties will appear, that let us customize the number of cuts, the smoothness and other minor properties.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/c58a3/blender-subdivision.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.859649122807014%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Subdivision of a mesh\"\n        title=\"Subdivision of a mesh\"\n        src=\"/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/0470c/blender-subdivision.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/6c669/blender-subdivision.jpg 285w,\n/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/882a4/blender-subdivision.jpg 570w,\n/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/0470c/blender-subdivision.jpg 1140w,\n/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/c58a3/blender-subdivision.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Subdivision of a mesh</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Remember: each number of cuts increment QUADRUPLICATE the number of polygon in your mesh.<br>\nIn the next chapter we will talk about advanced modeling techniques and tools.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Blender tutorial: introduction to basics of modeling - part 2","comments":true,"authors":["fabrizio_duroni"],"tags":["computer graphics","blender"],"date":"02 Jun 2018","description":"In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will continue to talk about the fundamental of modeling in Blender.","math":false,"image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#f8f8f8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/82c785dda340bcade8f49f5f78b43cf0/5ff8e/blender-subdivision.jpg","srcSet":"/static/82c785dda340bc